 Although there is much evidence regarding the effectiveness of warming for long operations, there is nothing looking at short procedures such as those undertaken in the daysurgery setting.

 A new carbon polymer blanket (HotDog Augustine Biomedical and Design) has been shown, in volunteer studies, to be as effective as forced air warming blankets (which are used for long operations) in preventing hypothermia.

 In contrast to forced air, the carbon polymer is reusable and has lower running-costs so is likely to be cheaper in the long term.

 This is particularly relevant in the day surgery setting where high numbers of patients are operated on.

 Additionally, and unlike the forced air warmers, the blanket can run on a battery so it can be applied from the moment the patient goes to sleep to the moment they wake up so it could actually prove more effective at preventing hypothermia in the clinical setting.

